To make an interface internal in TypeSpec so that it does not appear in the public interface of the generated Python SDK, you should use the `@Azure.ClientGenerator.Core.access(Azure.ClientGenerator.Core.Access.internal)` decorator on the interface. This will mark all operations within the interface as internal, and the interface itself will not be exposed in the public SDK surface.

However, it's important to note:
- If any operation within the interface is marked as public (either explicitly or by default), the interface or its operations may still be exposed.
- The access calculation logic in the Azure TypeSpec client generator ensures that if all operations in an interface are internal, the interface will not be exported in the generated SDK.
- The `@access` decorator must be applied to the interface, and all its operations must also be internal (either by inheritance from the interface or by explicit decoration).

Here is a runnable example:

```typespec
import "@azure-tools/typespec-client-generator-core";
using Azure.ClientGenerator.Core;

@Azure.ClientGenerator.Core.access(Azure.ClientGenerator.Core.Access.internal)
interface EvaluationResultsOperations {
  @get
  @Azure.ClientGenerator.Core.access(Azure.ClientGenerator.Core.Access.internal)
  listResults(): EvaluationResult[];
  @post
  @Azure.ClientGenerator.Core.access(Azure.ClientGenerator.Core.Access.internal)
  createResult(result: EvaluationResult): void;
}

model EvaluationResult {
  id: string;
  value: string;
}
```

With this setup, the `EvaluationResultsOperations` interface and its operations will be generated for internal use only and will not appear in the public Python SDK interface.

If you are still seeing the interface in the public SDK, double-check that:
- No operation under the interface is marked as public.
- The interface is not referenced by any public operation or type.

If you need to restrict this to Python only, you can use the `scope` parameter:

```typespec
@Azure.ClientGenerator.Core.access(Azure.ClientGenerator.Core.Access.internal, "python")
interface EvaluationResultsOperations { ... }
```

But remember, if the interface or its operations are referenced by public APIs, they will still be exposed as required by the access propagation rules.

