# language-basics#interfaces.md

# Interfaces

Interfaces are useful for grouping and reusing [operations](./operations.md).
You can declare interfaces using the `interface` keyword. Its name must be an [`identifier`](./identifiers.md).
\`\`\`typespec
interface SampleInterface {
  foo(): int32;
  bar(): string;
}
\`\`\`

## Composing interfaces

You can use the `extends` keyword to incorporate operations from other interfaces into a new interface.
Consider the following interfaces:
\`\`\`typespec
interface A {
  a(): string;
}
interface B {
  b(): string;
}
\`\`\`
You can create a new interface `C` that includes all operations from `A` and `B`:
\`\`\`typespec
interface C extends A, B {
  c(): string;
}
\`\`\`
This is equivalent to:
\`\`\`typespec
interface C {
  a(): string;
  b(): string;
  c(): string;
}
\`\`\`

## Interface templates

Interfaces can be templated. For more details on templates, [see templates](./templates.md).
\`\`\`typespec
interface ReadWrite<T> {
  read(): T;
  write(t: T): void;
}
\`\`\`

## Templating interface operations

Operations defined within an interface can also be templated. For more details on templates, [see templates](./templates.md).
\`\`\`typespec
interface ReadWrite<T> {
  read(): T;
  write<R>(t: T): R;
}
alias MyReadWrite = ReadWrite<string>;
op myWrite is MyReadWrite.write<int32>;
\`\`\`
:::caution
Any templated operation defined in an interface that is not instantiated will be omitted from the list of service operations.
This also applies when using `extends` on an interface that contains templated operations with unfilled template arguments.
\`\`\`typespec
interface ReadWrite<T> {
  read(): T;
  write<R>(t: T): R;
}
interface MyReadWrite extends ReadWrite<string> {} // Here, the `read()` operation is fully instantiated and will be included in a service definition. However, `write()` is not.
\`\`\`
When working with building block interfaces like this, use an alias to create your interface building block instead of `interface extends`. This way, the instantiated interface and its members will not be resolved in the service definition.
\`\`\`typespec
alias MyReadWrite = ReadWrite<string>;
op myRead is MyReadWrite.read;
op myWrite is MyReadWrite.write<int32>;
\`\`\`
:::"},{"document_source":"typespec_azure_docs","document_filename":"getstarted#versioning.md","document_title":"Versioning | Adding New Operations","document_link":"https://azure.github.io/typespec-azure/docs/getstarted/versioning","content":"# Versioning
## Adding New Operations
# getstarted#versioning.md

# Versioning

## Adding New Operations

You can add new operations to an interface for a specific version:
**Add a new operation in v2:**
\`\`\`tsp
@armResourceOperations
interface Employees {
  get is ArmResourceRead<Employee>;
  @added(Versions.v2)
  move is ArmResourceActionSync<Employee, MoveRequest, MoveResponse>;
}
\`\`\`"},{"document_source":"azure-sdk-docs-eng","document_filename":"docs#design#api-spec-gen-sdk-config.md","document_title":"SDK generation configuration","document_link":"https://eng.ms/docs/products/azure-developer-experience/design/api-spec-gen-sdk-config","content":"# SDK generation configuration
# docs#design#api-spec-gen-sdk-config.md

# SDK generation configuration

To generate SDK code based on REST API specifications, you need to configure the corresponding files.
- For TypeSpec, the configuration file is `tspconfig.yaml`.
- For OpenAPI, the configuration file is `readme.md`.

## Enable SDK generation

>[!IMPORTANT]
> You cannot enable SDK generation for both TypeSpec and OpenAPI simultaneously. Disable one before enabling the other.

### [TypeSpec](#tab/typespec)

Add the specific SDK language emitter settings to `tspconfig.yaml`. For example, to generate CSharp SDK code from your TypeSpecs:
1. Add `@azure-typespec/http-client-csharp-mgmt` to the `options` settings in `tspconfig.yaml`.
2. Refer to the 'ContosoWidgetManager' samples to set the default values for each SDK language emitter:
    - For management plane TypeSpecs, refer to [Contoso.Management tspconfig.yaml](https://aka.ms/azsdk/tspconfig-sample-mpg).
    - For data plane TypeSpecs, refer to [Contoso.WidgetManager tspconfig.yaml](https://aka.ms/azsdk/tspconfig-sample-dpg).
\`\`\``
"@azure-typespec/http-client-csharp-mgmt":
    namespace: "Azure.ResourceManager.Contoso"
    emitter-output-dir: "{output-dir}/{service-dir}/{namespace}"
\`\`\``

### [OpenAPI](#tab/openapi)

Configure the `swagger-to-sdk` section in `readme.md`. For example, to generate CSharp SDK code for your OpenAPIs:
1. Add `azure-sdk-for-net` to the list.
2. Add detailed settings to a separate file `readme.csharp.md` and place it in the same folder as `readme.md`.
\`\`\``

## Swagger to SDK

This section describes what SDK should be generated by the automatic system.
This is not used by Autorest itself.
\`\`\`yaml
$(swagger-to-sdk)
\`\`\`
swagger-to-sdk:
  - repo: azure-sdk-for-net
\`\`\`

## CSharp

See configuration in [readme.csharp.md](./readme.csharp.md)
\`\`\``
For more samples on configuring specific `readme.{language}.md`, refer to:
- [Sample Readmes for Management Plane Specifications](https://github.com/Azure/azure-rest-api-specs/tree/main/documentation/samplefiles)
- [Sample Readmes for Data Plane Specifications](https://github.com/Azure/azure-rest-api-specs/tree/main/documentation/samplefiles-dp)
- [Config SDK Guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-rest-api-specs/tree/main/documentation/code-gen)"},{"document_source":"typespec_docs","document_filename":"emitters#clients#http-client-python#reference#package-structure.mdx","document_title":"Namespaces | Controlling the Generation Directory","document_link":"https://typespec.io/docs/emitters/clients/http-client-python/reference/package-structure","content":"# Namespaces
## Controlling the Generation Directory
# emitters#clients#http-client-python#reference#package-structure.mdx

# Namespaces

## Controlling the Generation Directory

When migrating existing SDKs or working with brownfield services, you might need to place generated code in a specific subdirectory, like `_generated`. For these scenarios, you can use the [`namespace` configuration option](https://azure.github.io/typespec-azure/docs/libraries/typespec-client-generator-core/reference/emitter/#namespace) in your `tspconfig.yaml` file.
If you want the published SDK to follow closely with the package structure and namespaces in your TypeSpec file, you should also pass in the `package-name` flag with the desired value.

### Using the `namespace` Flag

The `namespace` option allows you to specify where the generated code should be placed within your package structure. This is particularly useful for cases where you want to:
1. Keep generated code isolated in a dedicated subdirectory
2. Maintain backward compatibility with existing SDK structures
3. Separate generated code from hand-written code
#### Example Configuration
In this example, we will take you through emitting generated code into a specific subdirectory (like `_generated`), with the idea that you will be fully-wrapping the generated code. Add the following to your `tspconfig.yaml`:
<Tabs>
<TabItem label="tspconfig.yaml" default>
\`\`\`yaml
emitters:
  "@typespec/http-client-python":
    namespace: "azure.keyvault.certificates._generated"
    package-name: "azure-keyvault-certificates"
\`\`\`
</TabItem>
<TabItem label="TypeSpec File">
\`\`\`typespec
namespace Azure.KeyVault.Certificates;
@service({
  title: "Azure Key Vault Certificate Client",
})
namespace Azure.Keyvault.Certificates {
  model Certificate {
    id: string;
    name: string;
    properties: CertificateProperties;
  }
  model CertificateProperties {
    created: utcDateTime;
    updated: utcDateTime;
    enabled: boolean;
  }
  @route("/certificates")
  interface CertificateOperations {
    @get list(): Certificate[];
    @get get(@path id: string): Certificate;
  }
}
\`\`\`
</TabItem>
<TabItem label="Generated Python SDK">
\`\`\`
azure-keyvault-certificates/
├── azure/
│   └── keyvault/
│       └── certificates/
│           ├── __init__.py
│           └── _generated/
│               ├── __init__.py
│               ├── _models.py
│               ├── _client.py
│               └── ...
├── setup.py
└── ...
\`\`\`
</TabItem>
</Tabs>"},{"document_source":"typespec_azure_docs","document_filename":"libraries#typespec-client-generator-core#reference#decorators.md","document_title":"Decorators | Azure.ClientGenerator.Core | `@access` {#@Azure.ClientGenerator.Core.access}","document_link":"https://azure.github.io/typespec-azure/docs/libraries/typespec-client-generator-core/reference/decorators","content":"# Decorators
