## Azure.ClientGenerator.Core
### `@protocolAPI` {#@Azure.ClientGenerator.Core.protocolAPI}
# libraries#typespec-client-generator-core#reference#decorators.md

# Decorators

## Azure.ClientGenerator.Core

### `@protocolAPI` {#@Azure.ClientGenerator.Core.protocolAPI}

Whether you want to generate an operation as a protocol method.
When applied to a namespace or interface, it affects all operations within that scope unless explicitly overridden.
\`\`\`typespec
@Azure.ClientGenerator.Core.protocolAPI(flag?: valueof boolean, scope?: valueof string)
\`\`\`
#### Target
The target operation, namespace, or interface.
`Operation | Namespace | Interface`
#### Parameters
| Name  | Type              | Description                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                |
| ----- | ----------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| flag  | `valueof boolean` | Whether to generate the operation as a protocol method or not.                                                                                                                                                                                             |
| scope | `valueof string`  | Specifies the target language emitters that the decorator should apply. If not set, the decorator will be applied to all language emitters by default.<br />You can use "!" to exclude specific languages, for example: !(java, python) or !java, !python. |
#### Examples
##### Apply to a single operation
\`\`\`typespec
@protocolAPI(false)
op test: void;
\`\`\`
##### Apply to all operations in an interface
\`\`\`typespec
@protocolAPI(false)
interface MyOperations {
  test1(): void;
  test2(): void;
}
\`\`\`
##### Apply to all operations in a namespace
\`\`\`typespec
@protocolAPI(false)
namespace MyService {
  op test1(): void;
  op test2(): void;
}
\`\`\`"},{"document_source":"static_typespec_qa","document_filename":"typespec_2025_08_21.md","document_title":"How to remove certain classes for Python SDK only | question","document_link":"","content":"# How to remove certain classes for Python SDK only
## question
# typespec_2025_08_21.md

# How to remove certain classes for Python SDK only

## question

Hi team, 
I was expecting there to be a way to remove specific classes for only the Python SDK in TypeSpec. I tried adding `@access(Access.internal, "python")` to those classes, but it didn’t work. Using `@removed` does remove the classes, but it removes them for all language SDKs, which isn’t what we want. 
Is there a recommended approach to exclude certain classes from generation only in the Python SDK? Any guidance would be greatly appreciated. Thanks!

## answer

If you want to remove specific classes only from the Python SDK in TypeSpec, using @access(Access.internal, "python") won’t work if the model is referenced by a public operation. To hide the model, you must also apply the decorator to the related operation that uses it.
In your case, the operation analyzeConversations uses the base type AnalyzeConversationTask, and the model you want to remove—LuisParameters—is a subtype of AnalysisParameters, which is used by ConversationTaskParameters. Since LuisParameters is part of a discriminated model (TargetIntentResult), it cannot be hidden from the wire-level API.
If the Python SDK board has recommended removing these types and you agree, then yes—adding @removed(version) is the only way to exclude them across all SDKs. Since the C# SDK has already shipped with these types, you could remove them in a C# patch release or the next planned release. This approach is acceptable for Python, but you need to confirm with the .NET team.
Also, it’s not possible to remove exported classes using _patch.py customization in the Python SDK."},{"document_source":"typespec_azure_docs","document_filename":"libraries#typespec-client-generator-core#reference#decorators.md","document_title":"Decorators | Azure.ClientGenerator.Core | `@clientNamespace` {#@Azure.ClientGenerator.Core.clientNamespace}","document_link":"https://azure.github.io/typespec-azure/docs/libraries/typespec-client-generator-core/reference/decorators","content":"# Decorators
## Azure.ClientGenerator.Core
### `@clientNamespace` {#@Azure.ClientGenerator.Core.clientNamespace}
# libraries#typespec-client-generator-core#reference#decorators.md

# Decorators

## Azure.ClientGenerator.Core

### `@clientNamespace` {#@Azure.ClientGenerator.Core.clientNamespace}

Changes the namespace of a client, model, enum or union generated in the client SDK.
By default, the client namespace for them will follow the TypeSpec namespace.
\`\`\`typespec
@Azure.ClientGenerator.Core.clientNamespace(rename: valueof string, scope?: valueof string)
\`\`\`
#### Target
The type you want to change the namespace for.
`Namespace | Interface | Model | Enum | Union`
#### Parameters
| Name   | Type             | Description                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                |
| ------ | ---------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| rename | `valueof string` | The rename you want applied to the object                                                                                                                                                                                                                  |
| scope  | `valueof string` | Specifies the target language emitters that the decorator should apply. If not set, the decorator will be applied to all language emitters by default.<br />You can use "!" to exclude specific languages, for example: !(java, python) or !java, !python. |
#### Examples
##### Change a namespace to a different name
\`\`\`typespec
@clientNamespace("ContosoClient")
namespace Contoso;
\`\`\`
##### Move a model to a different namespace
\`\`\`typespec
@clientNamespace("ContosoClient.Models")
model Test {
  prop: string;
}
\`\`\`"}]
